Amy,<br><br>
As a Vietnam Veteran, and a proude one at that, I pose the question to your question... Who is &quot;they&quot; that feel the Wall is a wall of shame ? Who is the &quot;They&quot; who think it will not help heal a nation from a time when our nation was divided almost as much as it was during the Civil War ? Who is the &quot;They&quot; who  pose this question and you may find your answers in that many who protested the war feel it is as you have ask, but for those who served, self included, I think it is a fitting tribute to those who gave the last full measure to their country. It is your choice today to ask these things of yourself because these Honored Men &amp; Women<br>
gave their life's for OUR freedoms, for OUR nation.<br><br>
 If you have the chance to talk to someone who did in fact protest the Vietnam war, ask them a question for me. Ask them where their momument is located and when was the last time they visited it. There indeed is one, but you see they are STILL to this day protesting the war and this nations veterans.. to the point that they have long lost sight of their own momunent. lost sight of their own honnor.<br><br>
 Last but not least there will always be those who will not like it for a lot of reasons... But Amy that IS THEIR RIGHT.<br>
It is their FREEDOM of choice that was bought with the blood of many a service man &amp; woman. Not Just Vietnam, but the civil war, WW I, Korea, WW II, the Gulf War and a dozen other wars/police actions/whatever... Add to that the service men &amp; women who die not in combat but in the every day military. How hany die being swept off the deck of an aircraft carrier ? How many die in Korea on the DMZ since <br>
that police action was over... The price of freedom is indeed a very high one as I know all to well. But I would answer my country's call today once more to uphold those freedoms and this time if it be my turn, so be it. I can think of no more noble or honnorable way to give me life.<br><br>
 Gary 'J.'<br>
Co. B 1/327 Inf 101st AIRBORNE Div '68-71
